equation_narrative.headline: Lysine emerges from polar-rich context after threonine dominates mid-layer representation
equation_narrative.story: Position 11 in ubiquitin sits in a polar-rich local environment (KTLTG[K]TITLE) with 3 structural contacts and 2 co-evolving positions. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation that shifts from small polar residues (S, T) to asparagine (peaking at L15, 16.9%) to threonine (dominating L16-23, peaking at 41.4% at L23). This reflects the model encoding the polar character of the local context rather than making predictions. The decision phase begins at L24-25 when MLP neurons start casting specific votes: lysine-specific features activate strongly, and K rises from 3.2% at L23 to 26.5% by L29. A massive attention-driven boost at L32 (+7.67 to K) pushes lysine to 89.8%, with final refinement settling at 78.3%. The model correctly identifies that this polar surface position requires a charged residue, with lysine winning over arginine and glutamine.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather structural and sequence context. Three structural contacts are read, with attention head L29:H10 showing strong structural attention (0.792) that will later drive the decision. Two co-evolving positions provide weak coupling signal. Early layers (L1-9) show generic polar/small residue features (F1:9146, F1:5480, F9:5728 all with 45-59 projection). The representation character shifts dramatically through mid-layers: asparagine peaks at L15 (16.9%), then threonine dominates L16-23 (peaking at 41.4% at L23). This threonine dominance reflects the model encoding the local polar context (KTLTG...TITLE with multiple T residues nearby) rather than predicting threonine. The logit lens projects toward small polar residues because the accumulated features are consistent with polar surface chemistry.
perception_phase.context_character: By L23, the representation encodes a polar surface environment with local threonine-rich sequence context. The structural contacts and co-evolutionary signal are modest, suggesting this position's identity is primarily determined by local sequence chemistry rather than long-range constraints.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 3 residues within contact distance, read by attention heads that will later drive K selection
Co-evolutionary signal: 2 coupled positions with weak signal, not a major constraint
Local sequence: KTLTG[K]TITLE context with multiple polar residues (T at -3, -1, +2, +4)
L1-9 features: Generic polar encoding (F9:5728, F9:1281, F9:2619 with 51-59 projection)
L18 features: Low-magnitude features (F18:7824, F18:3573 ~6 projection) indicate representation refinement phase

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L24-25 when MLP neurons begin casting amino-acid-specific votes. Lysine rises from 3.2% at L23 to 26.5% at L29, driven by K-specific MLP neurons (N24:2285 +0.335, N25:1119 +0.488). Arginine briefly competes (peaking at 20.6% at L29), but a massive attention-driven event at L32 (+7.67 from attention) pushes K to 89.8%. Final MLP refinement at L33 (-7.27 from MLP) adjusts the distribution, settling at 78.3% for K. High-projection attention features at L33 (F33:4166, F33:1408, F33:7165 all 84-89 projection) encode the final lysine decision.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-24, the representation shifts from encoding polar context to predicting specific amino acids. Threonine's 41.4% at L23 collapses as MLP neurons at L24 activate prediction channels: K-specific neurons (N24:2285, N24:1902) begin voting, while T-suppressing neurons (N24:4345 voting against with -0.449) erase the contextual signal. This is where perception becomes decision.

candidates.narrative: Lysine emerges decisively in the decision phase. At L24-25, K-specific MLP neurons activate (N24:2285 +0.335 for K, N25:1119 +0.488 for K), driving K from 3.2% at L23 to 26.5% at L29. A critical attention event at L32 (head H3 with +2.267 projection, local_attn=0.87) delivers a massive boost (+7.67 total), pushing K to 89.8%. Late-layer SAE features (F33:4166, F33:1408, F33:7165 with 84-89 projection) encode the final lysine decision. The model correctly identifies that this polar surface position requires a positively charged residue.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L24-25, dominates by L32 (89.8%), final 78.3%
key_evidence: N24:2285 (MLP, +0.335 to K) — early K-specific voter
N25:1119 (MLP, +0.488 to K) — strong K prediction neuron
F33:4166 (attn, 89.3 proj) — final K encoding feature
N30:3511 (MLP, +0.716 to K) — sustained K support

candidates.narrative: Glutamine emerges as a polar alternative in the decision phase, peaking at 13.4% at L27. Q-voting neurons activate at L27-29 (N27:3954 votes +0.265 for Q), but Q lacks the strong prediction channels that drive K. The model considers Q as a polar uncharged option, but the structural and sequence context favor the charged lysine. Q maintains ~10% through final layers as a plausible but suboptimal alternative.
candidates.key_layers: Rises L24-27, peaks at L27 (13.4%), settles at 10.5%
key_evidence: Polar character consistent with local context but lacks charge

candidates.narrative: Arginine competes as an alternative positive charge, peaking at 20.6% at L29. R-voting neurons (N24:5018 +0.288 for R, though also votes K) activate in the decision phase, and R briefly challenges K at L29. However, R lacks the sustained support that K receives: the massive L32 attention boost favors K, and R drops to 8.6% by L33. The model distinguishes between K and R, likely based on size or specific local sequence preferences.
candidates.key_layers: Rises L24-29, peaks at L29 (20.6%), drops to 8.6%
key_evidence: Competes at L29 but loses to K's attention boost at L32

candidates.narrative: Threonine dominates the logit lens from L16-23, peaking at 41.4% at L23. This reflects the model's representation encoding the local threonine-rich context (T at positions -3, -1, +2, +4) rather than predicting threonine. The representation is consistent with small polar residues because the accumulated features capture the polar chemistry of nearby positions. At L24, T-suppressing MLP neurons (N24:4345 voting -0.449 against K, favoring I/M/A) and the shift to amino-acid-specific prediction channels cause T to collapse from 41.4% to 13.5% by L29, finally settling at 0.7%.
candidates.key_layers: Dominates L16-23 (peaks 41.4% at L23), collapses L24+
key_evidence: Logit lens artifact reflecting local T-rich sequence context
N24:4345 (MLP, -0.449 to K, votes for I/M/A) — erases T signal
Representation character shifts to charged residues at L24+

candidates.narrative: Asparagine peaks at L15 (16.9%) during the mid-layer representation assembly phase. The logit lens projects toward N because the representation at this stage is consistent with polar, uncharged residues. This is not a prediction but rather reflects the model encoding polar character from structural contacts and local sequence. N collapses after L15 as the representation shifts toward threonine (L16-23) and then toward charged residues (L24+), settling at 0.85%.
key_evidence: Logit lens artifact during polar context assembly
Representation shifts to T-character L16-23, then to charged L24+

turning_points.description: The representation character shifts from asparagine-consistent (N peaks at 16.9% at L15) to threonine-dominant (T rises to 12.9% by L16). This reflects the model refining its encoding of the local polar context, with the threonine-rich sequence (KTLTG...TITLE) becoming the dominant feature. Multiple lead changes (L15 N→T, L16 T→K, L17 K→T) indicate active representation refinement rather than decision instability.

The critical perception-to-decision transition. Threonine's 41.4% at L23 (reflecting polar context encoding) collapses as MLP neurons at L24-25 activate amino-acid-specific prediction channels. K-voting neurons (N24:2285 +0.335, N25:1119 +0.488) drive K from 3.2% to 8.3%, while T-suppressing neurons erase the contextual signal. This is where the model shifts from 'what chemistry is here' to 'which amino acid should be here.'

The decisive commitment to lysine. At L29, K (26.5%) and R (20.6%) compete as charged alternatives. A massive attention-driven event at L32 (head H3 with +2.267 projection, total +7.67 to K) decisively favors lysine, pushing it to 89.8%. This attention head reads local sequence context (local_attn=0.87) and structural contacts (structural_attn=0.079), integrating all gathered information to commit to K over R.

deep_dives.label: Early SAE features L1-9
deep_dives.caption: Early layers encode generic polar/small residue features. F9:5728, F9:1281, F9:2619 (51-59 projection) capture the polar character being assembled from local sequence context. These are not prediction features but context encoders.

deep_dives.label: Mid-layer features L18
deep_dives.caption: L18 shows low-magnitude features (F18:7824, F18:3573 ~6 projection), indicating a representation refinement phase where the model is transitioning from context assembly to preparing for decision.

deep_dives.label: Decision MLP neurons L24-25
deep_dives.caption: The decision phase begins here. K-specific neurons (N24:2285 +0.335, N25:1119 +0.488) activate, while T-suppressing neurons (N24:4345 -0.449) erase the contextual polar signal. This is where amino-acid-specific prediction channels turn on.

deep_dives.label: K vs R competition L27-30
deep_dives.caption: Lysine and arginine compete as charged alternatives. K-voting neurons (N27:3829 +0.604, N30:3511 +0.716) sustain K, while R-voting neurons (N29:434 votes against with -0.415) and Q-voting neurons (N27:3954 +0.265) create a three-way competition among charged/polar options.

deep_dives.label: Decisive attention L32
deep_dives.caption: L32:H3 delivers the decisive boost (+2.267 projection, local_attn=0.87). This head reads local sequence context and integrates structural information to commit to lysine over arginine, pushing K from 63% to 89.8%.

deep_dives.label: Final encoding L33
deep_dives.caption: High-projection attention features (F33:4166, F33:1408, F33:7165 with 84-89 projection) encode the final lysine decision. These are K-specific prediction channels that crystallize the model's commitment.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts lysine by assembling a polar surface context through L1-23, then activating charged-residue prediction channels at L24+. The threonine dominance at L16-23 (peaking at 41.4%) was a logit-lens artifact reflecting the local T-rich sequence context, not a prediction. The decision crystallizes at L24-25 when K-specific MLP neurons activate, and a massive attention boost at L32 (L32:H3, +7.67) commits to lysine over arginine. The strongest evidence is the sustained K-specific neuron support (N24:2285, N25:1119, N30:3511) combined with the decisive L32 attention event that integrates local sequence and structural context to select the correct charged residue.
